title: For Sale:  10.5" AR Pistol Chambered in .300 Blackout plus reloading materials
postcontent:
First off, this is a pistol.  I had to select rifle due to Armslist not recognizing .300 BLK as a pistol caliber.  

Reason for sale: I was bit by the Blackout Bug, and eventually realized that I don't have the time to reload and shoot as much as my imagination thought i did.  So I am putting my entire Blackout related Reloading setup up for Sale or Trade.  I built this upper from a Colt 14.5" SOCOM Upper minus the barrel and muzzle device. So the upper receiver, bolt, and Troy VTAC handguard have been lightly used, all other parts are new.  The Upper and the Troy handguard had been previously spraypainted Tan.  There is a small amount of residual tan remaining, but it can be removed with a little elbow grease.  I've taken the condition into consideration in pricing. 

Pistol Specs:
Lower:
Anderson Arms Stripped Forged Lower with Trigger Guard (looks better and more like a Billet Lower)
PSA Carbine Buffer Assembly 
PSA LPK
MAGPUL BAD Lever
Ambi Safety
KNS Anti-Rotation Pins
Slidefire Solutions Trigger Assembly (Packaging claimed it was a 2 stage, but its near identical to a Milspec Single Stage, similar to ALG QMS Trigger, very smooth)

Upper:
Colt Upper Receiver 
Colt Full Auto Bolt Carrier Group
Rainier Arms Match 10.5" .300 Blackout Barrel
Colt Low Profile Gas Block
Colt Charging Handle
Spikes Pistol length Gas Tube
Troy Claymore Linear Compensator 
Troy VTAC 11" Alpha Battlerail (older style)
Magpul polymer picatinny rail mounted on the bottom for an angled fore-grip or vertical foregrip.  
NOTE: this handgun has a barrel length less than 16" and an overall length greater than 26". This makes it a Title 1 "other" firearm.  Therefore, under Federal laws, it can legally have a forward vertical grip.
If the overall length was less than 26", then it would be a Title 1 "handgun" and the addition of a forward vertical grip would make it a Title 2 AOW (tax stamp required). 

$950 for the above pistol.

Reloading Materials:
RCBS Small Base .300 Blackout Dies w/ Taper Crimp http://www.midwayusa.com/product/261325/rcbs-ar-series-small-base-2-die-set-with-taper-crimp-300-aac-blackout

75 Hornady Soft Point 110 Grain projectiles (older stock)
200 Converted mixed-stamp 300 Blackout Brass. (primed and tumbled, sized, trimmed, Primer pockets swaged)
300 non-converted 5.56 brass.
Chop Saw with mount for first step of converting 5.56 brass to 300 Blackout
1 1# container of H110 powder (this stuff is rarer than unicorn poop)
~50 handloaded 110 gn rounds.  

Optional Items (can be added to bump trade value)
Troy Micro Flip Front and Rear sights  just like http://www.laruetactical.com/sight-set-troy-micro-low-profile-folding-battle-sights-front-rear-black
Sightmark Holographic Sight & 3X Magnifier with flip to side mount.
Primary Arms MD-SP Micro-dot sight



Or trade for a Colt, Smith & Wesson, Dan Wesson or Ruger .357 revolver plus cash.  .357 Reloading supplies to feed the weapon are also desired.  2-4" barrel preferred.

title: For Sale:  Extremely Scarce and Historically Significant 1900 Luger US Test Trial Pistol
postcontent: For Sale: Up for sale is one if the rarest Lugers one would hope to encounter with only 174 examples still known to exist. This pistol is in outstanding condition for a test Luger as most were beaten beyond recognition and were pitted from one end to the other from the humid Climates in the philliphnes and Cuba and most of them encountered today are mismatched and reblued. This one is all numbers matching and 100% original finish with about 40-50% of its original rust blue finish with a small spot of pitting on the barrel. This gun belongs in a meuseum or an advanced collection. Below is some information about the 1000 test Lugers. One thousand test Lugers (7.65 cal) were delivered to the U. S. Springfield Armory in late 1901. Most were distributed to U.S. Cavalry troops involved in police actions in the Philippines and Cuba. As the American Cavalry troops had used revolvers (Colt .45 and .38) for over 30 years, the small caliber, complex Luger, was viewed with some suspicion and not readily accepted. There were complaints as to small caliber, safety while riding from horseback, and unreliable action. As a result of these reports 50 Lugers in caliber 9mm were briefly tested by the Army in 1904-1906 and three Lugers in .45 caliber were tested. Ultimately the Luger was rejected in favor of the Colt 1911. he characteristics that separate these U.S.-American Eagle-Test Lugers from other Model 1900 Lugers are: the lack of proofs, the lack of a Germany import stamp and the last two digits of the Lugers serial numbers on the right end of the takedown lever (instead of the left lower side) which this guns displays all of. This serial number is also listed on the bannerman sales invoice when he bought all the remaining Lugers that survived testing from the us army ordnance department confirming beyond a shadow of a doubt this is indeed A us test trials pistol. Will consider trades on collectable coins from the 1800s, gold and silver coins or gold and silver bullion. Take I look around at recent auctions and you will see you will never find another of these pistols close to this cheap. I'm willing to ship to any FFL or C&R license holder. Email, call, or text REDACTED.

Gen II billet lower receiver specifications and features:
